<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Role_and_evolution">Role and evolution</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sitting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Role and evolution">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:DeTroy.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/DeTroy.jpg/220px-DeTroy.jpg" width="220" height="175" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/DeTroy.jpg/330px-DeTroy.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/DeTroy.jpg/440px-DeTroy.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1196" data-file-height="950" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:DeTroy.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Women reclining in chairs. Painting by <a href="/wiki/Jean-Fran%C3%A7ois_de_Troy" class="mw-redirect" title="Jean-François de Troy">Jean-François de Troy</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt_helfigur_sittande_(photo_by_Sune_Frack_on_Flickr).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt_helfigur_sittande_%28photo_by_Sune_Frack_on_Flickr%29.jpg/220px-B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt_helfigur_sittande_%28photo_by_Sune_Frack_on_Flickr%29.jpg" width="220" height="330" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt_helfigur_sittande_%28photo_by_Sune_Frack_on_Flickr%29.jpg/330px-B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt_helfigur_sittande_%28photo_by_Sune_Frack_on_Flickr%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt_helfigur_sittande_%28photo_by_Sune_Frack_on_Flickr%29.jpg/440px-B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt_helfigur_sittande_%28photo_by_Sune_Frack_on_Flickr%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2243" data-file-height="3364" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt_helfigur_sittande_(photo_by_Sune_Frack_on_Flickr).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Swedish actor <a href="/wiki/B%C3%B6rje_Ahlstedt" title="Börje Ahlstedt">Börje Ahlstedt</a> sitting on a chair</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Although chairs with backrests have only been common in Europe since the 16th century and office workers sitting at work was uncommon even in the early 20th century,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/British_Chiropractic_Association" title="British Chiropractic Association">British Chiropractic Association</a> said in 2006 that 32% of the British population spent more than ten hours per day sitting down.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Positions">Positions</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sitting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Positions">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="On_the_floor">On the floor</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sitting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: On the floor">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The most common ways of sitting on the floor involves bending the knees. One can also sit with the legs unbent, using something solid as support for the back or leaning on one's arms. Sitting with bent legs can be done with the legs mostly parallel or by crossing them over each other.</p>
<p>A common cross-legged position is with the lower part of both legs folded towards the body, crossing each other at the ankle or calf, with both ankles on the floor, sometimes with the feet tucked under the knees or thighs. The position is known in several European languages as <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/tailor_style" class="extiw" title="wikt:tailor style">tailor style</a>, from the traditional working posture of <a href="/wiki/Tailor" title="Tailor">tailors</a>;<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> compare <a href="/wiki/Tailor%27s_bunion" title="Tailor's bunion">tailor's bunion</a>. It is also named after various plains-dwelling <a href="/wiki/Nomad" title="Nomad">nomads</a>: in American English <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Indian_style" class="extiw" title="wikt:Indian style">Indian style</a>, in many European languages "Turkish style", and in Japanese <a href="/wiki/Agura" title="Agura">agura</a> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%83%A1%E5%BA%A7" class="extiw" title="wikt:??">??</a></span><span style="display:none">,</span> <i>The sitting style of non-Han ethnics (particularly Turks, Mongols and other Central Asians.)</i>)</span>. In yoga it is known as <a href="/wiki/Sukhasana" title="Sukhasana">sukhasana</a>.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="On_a_raised_seat">On a raised seat</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sitting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: On a raised seat">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Buddhist_bronze_sculpture_NMND.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Buddhist_bronze_sculpture_NMND.JPG/220px-Buddhist_bronze_sculpture_NMND.JPG" width="220" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Buddhist_bronze_sculpture_NMND.JPG/330px-Buddhist_bronze_sculpture_NMND.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Buddhist_bronze_sculpture_NMND.JPG/440px-Buddhist_bronze_sculpture_NMND.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2448" data-file-height="3264" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Buddhist_bronze_sculpture_NMND.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
An <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> <a href="/wiki/Buddha" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddha">Buddha</a>, seated</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Most raised surfaces at the appropriate height can be used as <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/seat" class="extiw" title="wiktionary:seat">seats</a> for humans, whether they are made for the purpose, such as <a href="/wiki/Chair" title="Chair">chairs</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chair" title="Chair">stools</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bench_(furniture)" title="Bench (furniture)">benches</a>, or not. While the buttocks are nearly always rested on the raised surface, there are many differences in how one can hold one's legs and back.</p>
<p>There are two major styles of sitting on a raised surface. The first has one or two of the legs in front of the sitting person; in the second, sitting astride something, the legs incline outwards on either side of the body.</p>
<p>The feet can rest on the floor, or on a <a href="/wiki/Footrest" class="mw-redirect" title="Footrest">footrest</a>, which can keep them vertical, horizontal, or at an angle in between. They can also dangle if the seat is sufficiently high. Legs can be kept right to the front of the body, spread apart, or one crossed over the other.</p>
<p>The upper body can be held upright, recline to either side or backwards, or one can lean forward.</p>
<h3><span id="Yoga,_traditions,_and_spirituality"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Yoga.2C_traditions.2C_and_spirituality">Yoga, traditions, and spirituality</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sitting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Yoga, traditions, and spirituality">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Tea_ceremony_performing_2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Tea_ceremony_performing_2.jpg/220px-Tea_ceremony_performing_2.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Tea_ceremony_performing_2.jpg/330px-Tea_ceremony_performing_2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Tea_ceremony_performing_2.jpg/440px-Tea_ceremony_performing_2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="640" data-file-height="480" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Tea_ceremony_performing_2.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/Japanese_tea_ceremony" title="Japanese tea ceremony">Japanese tea ceremony</a> is performed sitting in <a href="/wiki/Seiza" title="Seiza">seiza</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>There are many seated positions in various traditions and rituals. Four examples are:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Seiza" title="Seiza">Seiza</a> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">??</span>) "correct sitting"</span> is a <a href="/wiki/Japanese_language" title="Japanese language">Japanese word</a> which describes the traditional formal way of sitting in Japan. A related position is <a href="/wiki/Kiza" class="mw-redirect" title="Kiza">kiza</a> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">??</span>)</span>, which differs in the tops of the feet being raised off the ground.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Vajrasana_(yoga)" title="Vajrasana (yoga)">Vajrasana</a> (Diamond Pose) is a <a href="/wiki/Yoga" title="Yoga">yoga</a> posture (<a href="/wiki/Asana" title="Asana">asana</a>) similar to seiza.</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Lotus_position" title="Lotus position">lotus position</a> involves resting each foot on the opposite thigh so that the soles of the feet face upwards.</li>
<li>The Burmese position, named so because of its use in <a href="/wiki/Buddhist" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddhist">Buddhist</a> sculptures in <a href="/wiki/Burma" class="mw-redirect" title="Burma">Burma</a>, places both feet in front of the pelvis with knees bent and touching the floor to the sides. The heels are pointing toward pelvis or upward, and toes are pointed so that the tops of the feet lie on the ground. This looks similar to the cross legged position, but the feet are not placed underneath the thigh of the next leg, therefore the legs do not cross. Instead, one foot is placed in front of the other.</li>
</ul>
<p>In various <a href="/wiki/Mythology" title="Mythology">mythologies</a> and <a href="/wiki/Folk_magic" class="mw-redirect" title="Folk magic">folk magic</a>, sitting is a magical act that connects the person who sits with other persons, states or places.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Health_risks"><span id="Health_effects"></span>Health risks</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sitting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Health risks">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:School_of_Rembrandt_-_Sitting_nude.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/School_of_Rembrandt_-_Sitting_nude.jpg/180px-School_of_Rembrandt_-_Sitting_nude.jpg" width="180" height="242" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/School_of_Rembrandt_-_Sitting_nude.jpg/270px-School_of_Rembrandt_-_Sitting_nude.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5a/School_of_Rembrandt_-_Sitting_nude.jpg 2x" data-file-width="298" data-file-height="400" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:School_of_Rembrandt_-_Sitting_nude.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
